<p><strong>Non-jobs:</strong> running or editing payroll, tax filing, emplo=
yee record management, per-employee pay stubs. Those live in the Payroll mo=
dule proper.</p>
<h2 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-7.Contextscenarios">7. Context scenarios</h2=
>
<p><span class=3D"status-macro aui-lozenge aui-lozenge-visual-refresh aui-l=
ozenge-complete">DESKTOP RESEARCH</span> and <span class=3D"status-macro au=
i-lozenge aui-lozenge-visual-refresh aui-lozenge-progress">SME INTERVIEW</s=
pan>, grounded in the domain and verified behavior. Each ends with how it p=
lays out today.</p>
<p><strong>A. Just after a pay run.</strong> The bookkeeper runs the monthl=
y payroll and opens the dashboard to confirm the total and that housing all=
owance landed in its own category. Today: the widget shows the categories i=
f the dashboard is on the right company and the range covers the run; there=
 is no quick period control, so they adjust dates by hand.</p>
<p><strong>B. Budget season.</strong> The executive pastor wants salary vs =
benefits vs housing, year to date. Today: this year's split is available on=
ce the range is set to year to date.</p>
<p><strong>C. A number looks wrong.</strong> Benefits look high. The bookke=
eper wants to see which employees or checks drove it. Today: no drill from =
the widget, and Earnings Inquiry only answers per named employee, so they g=
o employee by employee or run a report.</p>
<p><strong>D. Multi-entity org.</strong> A church that also runs a school a=
nd a daycare wants payroll for just the school's pay group. Today: all pay =
groups are combined; no way to isolate one. (SME interview, 8b; pay group d=
eferred per 8c and 10.4.)</p>
<p><strong>E. Board meeting prep.</strong> The treasurer needs a defensible=
 by-category payroll total. Today: they read the widget and retype the figu=
res into their board doc; no export.</p>
<p><strong>F. New or payroll-free church.</strong> A church that does not r=
un payroll here, or a brand-new setup, selects the widget and sees "No reco=
rds to display" with a blank total. Today: no explanation of what the widge=
t is or how to populate it.</p>
<h2 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-8.Competitorandanalogbenchmark">8. Competito=
r and analog benchmark</h2>
<p><span class=3D"status-macro aui-lozenge aui-lozenge-visual-refresh aui-l=
ozenge-complete">DESKTOP RESEARCH</span> Church payroll tools compete on cl=
ergy-specific handling (dual status, housing allowance) and increasingly on=
 clear dashboards. None expose exactly a "distributions by compensation typ=
e" dashboard widget, but the category-of-pay breakdown is a common report, =
and the market baseline for a dashboard figure is one-click drill to detail=
.</p>
<div id=3D"expander-2143723693" class=3D"expand-container">
<div id=3D"expander-control-2143723693" class=3D"expand-control">
<span class=3D"expand-control-icon"><img style=3D"vertical-align:middle;" c=
lass=3D"expand-control-image" src=3D"9b45ae8c85c16a66aad904c0270f58d8cbd79c=
476bc8d003bcec7b51f05e1f85" width=3D"16" height=3D"16"></span><span class=
=3D"expand-control-text">Benchmark detail</span>
</div>
<div id=3D"expander-content-2143723693" class=3D"expand-content">
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"960" data-layout=3D"default" class=3D"confluence=
Table">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Product</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Relevant pattern</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>MinistryWorks (Brotherhood Mutual)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Built for ministry and clergy tax law; dedicated payroll specialists; ha=
ndles clergy housing allowance natively. Sets the domain bar for category c=
orrectness (<a href=3D"https://www.techrepublic.com/article/top-church-payr=
oll-services/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">TechRepublic</a>).<=
/p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>QuickBooks Payroll</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Multiple pay types including clergy housing allowance; powerful payroll =
reports to see who was paid what and when; drillable report layer (<a href=
=3D"https://quickbooks.intuit.com/payroll/church/" class=3D"external-link" =
rel=3D"nofollow">QuickBooks</a>).</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Gusto</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Polished dashboard; handles FICA exemption for ministers and housing all=
owance payouts; automatic breakdowns marketed as a feature (<a href=3D"http=
s://theleadpastor.com/tools/best-church-payroll-software/" class=3D"externa=
l-link" rel=3D"nofollow">The Lead Pastor</a>).</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Rippling / Paycor / Dayforce</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Configurable pay categories and real-time dashboards with audit trails; =
enterprise-grade drill into any figure. Multi-entity payroll platforms trea=
t legal entity, location, and <strong>pay group</strong> as first-class sco=
ping units, with consolidated reporting that can be filtered down to one un=
it.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Takeaway: the market leaders make the by-category view <strong>drillable=
</strong> and treat clergy categories as first-class. This widget already h=
as the right grain; where it trails is drill and status. (Market tools also=
 lean on period comparison, but that is out of scope here, see 10.3.)</p>
<h2 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-8b.SMEinterview:BenLane(13Jul2026)">8b. SME =
interview: Ben Lane (13 Jul 2026)</h2>
<p><span class=3D"status-macro aui-lozenge aui-lozenge-visual-refresh aui-l=
ozenge-progress">SME INTERVIEW</span> From "Accounting Dashboards: SME Inte=
rview &amp; Hallway Testing" (<a href=3D"https://app.heymarvin.com/projects=
/63398/media/41887339/" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">Marvin</a>=
). The SME is a long-tenured Shelby trainer and onboarding specialist.</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"1077" data-layout=3D"default" class=3D"confluenc=
eTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>What the SME said</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Consequence</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Usage signal.</strong> Named payroll distributions among the wid=
gets clients "like really well", and Payroll is a core module.</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Reach is high. Raises the payoff of every improvement here</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Date range is for pay periods, mostly by month.</strong> "They'r=
e doing it by pay period and want to do it by a month"; finding the pay cyc=
le is the more common reason to change dates</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>The period control is the primary control of this widget. Month is the m=
ost common window</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Keep a custom / specific date option always.</strong> Auto perio=
d presets "would work" as a convenience, "just as long as they still do hav=
e an option to do specific"</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Any presets are additive, never a replacement. Custom range must always =
be present</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Filter by pay group.</strong> Orgs may run "a daycare, or a scho=
ol, and a church"; they may all pay on the same frequency but "want to be a=
ble to limit it by pay group". Pay group is already a payroll function. "If=
 you could do it by pay group and by date, I think that would solve it"</p>=
</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A real, specific need for multi-entity orgs. But see 8c: the pay-group d=
ata model is not understood well enough to design a filter against yet</p><=
/td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Drill to detail is loved elsewhere.</strong> Clicking a line on =
a report to see its detail is "a feature that is loved by our clients"; the=
 SME would welcome the same on the dashboard</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Supports serving JTBD 5. Users expect it to feel like the report drill t=
hey already know</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Company switch should be global.</strong> When someone changes c=
ompany, most want every widget to follow; per-widget company benefits only =
a few large multi-entity HQs</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Confirms the company-scoping constraint (9.3)</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<h2 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-8c.Paygroups:whatwefound,andwhythepictureisn=
otyetclearenoughtodesignagainst">8c. Pay groups: what we found, and why the=
 picture is not yet clear enough to design against</h2>
<p><span class=3D"status-macro aui-lozenge aui-lozenge-visual-refresh aui-l=
ozenge-success">VERIFIED LIVE</span> (95301 and beta1) and <span class=3D"s=
tatus-macro aui-lozenge aui-lozenge-visual-refresh aui-lozenge-progress">CO=
NFIRMED BY OISIN CURRAN</span> (page comments, 16 Jul). This section docume=
nts what we could and could not establish about pay groups, because it dete=
rmines whether a pay-group filter (JTBD 4, 10.4) can responsibly be designe=
d this pass.</p>
<p><strong>What we established:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Pay groups exist and are set up under Payroll &gt; Modify &gt; <strong>E=
mployer Information</strong>, as a named list (the defaults "Group A" throu=
gh "Group E" on the test company). On that screen a pay group is just a nam=
e among other employer settings; it does not visibly carry its own pay freq=
uency or schedule. <span class=3D"status-macro aui-lozenge aui-lozenge-visu=
al-refresh aui-lozenge-success">VERIFIED LIVE</span></p></li>
<li>
<p>The multi-entity need is real and specific: an org running, say, a dayca=
re, a school, and a church would use pay groups to separate them, and wants=
 to read one entity's distributions without the others mixed in (SME, 8b). =
For a single-entity church (everyone in one group, or the A=E2=80=93E defau=
lts untouched) a pay-group filter adds nothing.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>What we could not resolve, and this is the problem:</strong> the=
 relationship between the several overlapping payroll concepts is unclear, =
and they are easy to conflate. There is <strong>compensation type</strong> =
(the widget's existing category grain, set up under CompensationInformation=
, and one employee can have several), there is <strong>pay group</strong> (=
set up under Employer Information), and there is also a <strong>pay type</s=
trong> concept encountered in the product. On the individual employee recor=
d there is no field plainly labelled "pay group", so how an employee actual=
ly maps to a pay group, and how pay group relates to pay type and to compen=
sation type, is not something we could pin down from the UI in this pass. W=
e also could not confirm whether an employee can belong to more than one gr=
oup, or, critically, whether a historical distribution record (PRHistory / =
PRHistoryCompensation) even carries a pay-group key at all. Oisin flagged t=
his last point as one for Value Labs, noting the pay/hours breakdown is sto=
red but not whether the pay-group link sits on the distribution table or el=
sewhere.</p>
<p><strong>Why this matters for design:</strong> a filter is only as sound =
as the data model under it. We cannot design a pay-group filter, decide whe=
ther it is one selector or several, whether it composes with the date range=
, what it should return when an employee has moved groups mid-year, without=
 first understanding what a pay group is in the data and how it attaches to=
 a distribution. Getting that understanding is not a quick lookup; it is a =
proper investigation into the payroll data model (pay group vs pay type vs =
compensation type, and their mapping to history), and it needs someone who =
can see the schema, i.e. Value Labs. That is significant effort, disproport=
ionate to bolting one optional filter onto one widget unless the multi-enti=
ty need is prioritised in its own right.</p>
<h1 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-PartC.Designerbrief">Part C. Designer brief<=
/h1>
<h2 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-9.Thebrief">9. The brief</h2>
<div class=3D"panel" style=3D"background-color: #EAE6FF;border-color: #998D=
D9;border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"panelContent" style=3D"background-color: #EAE6FF;">
<p>Jobs, states, and constraints in one place. This is the problem the desi=
gn must solve. Read with Section 10 (the significant decisions and trade-of=
fs) and Section 11 (the review of the current redesign attempt). Design ide=
as appear as options with their reasoning, for the designer to weigh, not a=
s instructions.</p>
</div>
</div>
<h3 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-9.1Whattopreserve">9.1 What to preserve</h3>
<p>The compensation-type grain is correct and hard-won; do not revert it to=
 a per-check list. The live-query freshness (no stale cache) is a strength.=
 Labeled date inputs are already better than the sibling widget.</p>
