</table>
</div>
<h3 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-9.3Constraints">9.3 Constraints</h3>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"1077" data-layout=3D"default" class=3D"confluenc=
eTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Constraint</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>What it means</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Widget views (established shell)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>The widget lives in the platform's existing set of <strong>views</strong=
> =E2=80=94 a content-depth vector, not a size vector: <strong>glance, deta=
il, explore</strong>. Any view may span 3, 4, 6, or 12 columns of the 12-co=
lumn grid depending on screen width, breakpoint, and the view itself, so "v=
iew" describes content depth, not a fixed footprint. There is also a <stron=
g>focus</strong> state: an isolate-and-focus overlay (the widget expanded i=
n place over the dashboard), not a fourth view and not navigation to anothe=
r page. This is a made and built decision, not a question; it is the materi=
al to design within. The source of truth for the views is the widget shell =
component in the Pathway master file: <a href=3D"https://www.figma.com/desi=
gn/3sw45aVcngFAmpbP6cfrXP/%E2%9D%87%EF%B8%8F--Pathway-Design-System--Master=
-File--MB-2.0-?node-id=3D40009622-39702" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nof=
ollow">widget shell (Figma)</a>. See 10.8 for a suggested content mapping a=
cross the views.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Clergy tax categories are first-class</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Housing allowance, SECA allowance, and the clergy/lay split are meaningf=
ul groupings, not arbitrary line items. Category labels must be the org's o=
wn, shown faithfully.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Categories are org-defined and variable</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Compensation categories come from the org's own setup. Names and counts =
differ per church; never assume a fixed category list. Confirmed live: "AA =
Aid", "Administration Staff".</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Regulated figures</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Payroll totals feed W-2s, tax filings, and board reporting. The widget s=
hould signal how current its data is.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Rights and PII</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Pay data is sensitive. Visibility follows user rights; any drill to per-=
employee detail must respect payroll-view permissions.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Company scoping</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Company (with fiscal year, period, bank account) is <strong>global produ=
ct context</strong>, set in the top-right switcher for the whole Accounting=
 product, not a per-widget control. The widget reads whatever company is ac=
tive there (verified). Company switch is global for the majority (SME, 8b).=
 A widget-level scope (such as pay group) would be a genuinely new kind of =
control, not an extension of company scoping.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Accessibility (Pathway AA)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Amounts must be readable as text, not hover-only. The breakdown must be =
programmatically associated with its labels. Controls and any icon-only but=
tons must be named and keyboard-reachable. The current widget fails this on=
 real data.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Plain language</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Part-time non-specialist users. "Total paid", "Housing allowance", not c=
odes or jargon.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Works within the widget, not new pages</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>For now, everything the widget offers (including any detail view) should=
 live in the widget and its focus overlay, not spawn new module pages or re=
ports.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<h2 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-10.Significantdesigndecisionsandtrade-offs">=
10. Significant design decisions and trade-offs</h2>
<p>This section records the decisions that shape the widget and, above all,=
 <em>why</em>, so the reasoning is not lost. It names user needs and the ev=
idence behind them. Where it mentions a possible solution, that is offered =
as an option with its rationale for the designer to decide, not as a spec.<=
/p>
<h3 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-10.1Theperiodcontrolistheprimarycontrol,andi=
tmustservetwomindsets">10.1 The period control is the primary control, and =
it must serve two mindsets</h3>
<p><strong>Decision:</strong> the single most important control is how the =
user sets the period the total covers. As a user, I need to easily control =
the period I am looking at, or set my own custom range.</p>
<p><strong>Why it is not the same as Deposits On Hand:</strong> Deposits On=
 Hand shows a <em>balance</em>, which has a meaningful "as of today" value,=
 so it can lead with today's number. Payroll Distributions shows a <em>flow=
</em>: money paid over a span. There is no single-day value (most days nobo=
dy is paid), so the total only means something across a window. The control=
 therefore has to define a span, and the headline number is the <strong>sum=
 across that span</strong>, not a latest value.</p>
<p><strong>Two mindsets to serve (Section 5):</strong> operational users (P=
1) think by pay run ("did the last payroll look right"); reporting users (P=
2, P3) think in calendar and fiscal periods ("what have we spent this year"=
), which is also how boards, budgets, and tax filings are framed. The SME c=
onfirms both: pay-period thinking, "mostly by month", and a strong year-to-=
date orientation elsewhere in the same session. The period control needs to=
 answer both without forcing either group into the other's vocabulary. Cust=
om range must always be available (SME, hard requirement).</p>
<h3 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-10.2Thehardtrade-off:whatunitshouldtheperiod=
comein?">10.2 The hard trade-off: what unit should the period come in?</h3>
<p>This is the crux, and it was worked through carefully because the obviou=
s answer is wrong in a way that matters for a regulated figure. Three candi=
date units were considered.</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-table-width=3D"1200" data-layout=3D"default" class=3D"confluenc=
eTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Option</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>The idea</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Why it falls short</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>A. Calendar spans</strong> (this month, this quarter, YTD, this =
year, custom)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Familiar units that match how boards, budgets, and tax filings are frame=
d. Always well-defined regardless of how an org is structured</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>A calendar month does not always contain the same number of pay runs. Bi=
weekly pay produces 26 periods a year, so two months each year carry a thir=
d paycheck (the documented "three-paycheck month"). This makes calendar win=
dows unreliable for any period-over-period math, though that is now moot si=
nce comparison is out of scope (10.3). For simply displaying a chosen span'=
s total, calendar spans are fine</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>B. Declared pay cycle</strong> (know the org is biweekly, count =
back)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Would be the most "native" framing, aligned to how payroll actually runs=
</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Rejected. We cannot know an org's schedule in advance, and different pay=
 groups within one org can run on different cadences, so there is no single=
 "the pay cycle" at the company level</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>C. Retrospective pay dates</strong> (most recent pay date, last =
3, last 6, read from history)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>Needs no schedule prediction: the real check dates already sit in PRHist=
ory (Section 2)</p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>"The most recent pay date" is only well-defined if there is one. An org =
running a monthly church and a weekly daycare has no single last pay date, =
and "last 3 pay dates" could silently return three weekly daycare runs and =
omit the church entirely. Making it safe would require detecting the org's =
cadence structure, which we have no reliable way to do</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><strong>Where this lands.</strong> The recommended direction is <strong>=
calendar-based spans (A) as the period unit</strong>, because they are well=
-defined for every org regardless of pay-group or cadence structure, they m=
atch the reporting mindset, and the always-available custom range covers th=
e operational "exact pay run" case. The pay-date unit (C) was seriously con=
sidered but depends on cadence detection we cannot perform, and its main ad=
vantage (equal-event-count comparison) is no longer relevant now that compa=
rison is out of scope (10.3).</p>
<h3 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-10.3Trendandcomparison:rejected">10.3 Trend =
and comparison: rejected</h3>
<p><strong>Status: rejected for this widget.</strong> "Trend and comparison=
" means any element whose job is to express this period <em>relative to ano=
ther period</em>: a trend line or mini-chart-over-time, a trend or delta ba=
dge ("+12% vs last month"), an up/down change arrow, or any "vs last period=
" figure, at any view including glance. None of these belong on this widget=
.</p>
<p><strong>This is distinct from proportion, which is kept.</strong> Showin=
g each category's share of the selected period's total (percent-of-total, r=
elative bar length) is <em>within-period</em> and stays in scope; it is par=
t of reading the breakdown, not trending it.</p>
<p><strong>Why rejected:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Not worth the complexity.</strong> Doing period-over-period math=
 correctly on payroll is hard: because of the three-paycheck-month effect (=
10.2), two calendar periods can contain different numbers of pay runs, so a=
 naive comparison misleads on a regulated figure. Getting it right is dispr=
oportionate to the value.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Out of scope for this pass.</strong> No SME asked for comparison=
 on this widget (the SME raised it for Budget-vs-Actual, not here); demand =
is inferred from general dashboard practice, not observed. It would need de=
dicated research and a solid use and business case before it is worth build=
ing.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>The widget shows the selected period's own numbers, the grand total and =
the category breakdown, and does not editorialize them against any other pe=
riod. A concrete example of the kind of need that <em>would</em> reopen thi=
s: comparing one category (say PTO) for one pay group across two periods. T=
hat is a legitimate question, but it is exactly the period-over-period math=
 this decision defers until there is a validated use and business case.</p>
<h3 id=3D"PayrollDistributions-10.4Paygroup:deferred,notbeingbroughtinthisp=
ass">10.4 Pay group: deferred, not being brought in this pass</h3>
<p><strong>Decision:</strong> do not add a pay-group filter in this pass. T=
he need is real, a multi-entity org (daycare / school / church) wanting to =
read one entity's distributions is a genuine, specific job raised by the SM=
E (8b), but we cannot responsibly design the filter yet, because we do not =
understand the underlying model well enough (8c).</p>
<p><strong>Why deferred:</strong> the payroll model has several overlapping=
 concepts, compensation type, pay group, and pay type, whose relationships =
we could not pin down from the product, and there is no clearly-labelled pa=
y-group field on the employee record. More decisively, we do not know wheth=
er a historical distribution record even carries a pay-group key. Without t=
hat, every design question (one selector or several, how it composes with t=
he date range, what it returns when an employee has changed groups) is unan=
swerable, and any filter risks producing wrong figures on regulated data. E=
stablishing the model properly is a significant investigation into the payr=
oll data model, needing Value Labs and schema access, not a quick check.</p=
>
<p><strong>So:</strong> pay group is parked. It becomes worth doing when th=
e multi-entity need is prioritised in its own right and the data-model inve=
stigation (8c) is funded. It is not a small add-on to this widget. If and w=
hen it is picked up, this page (8b, 8c) holds the need and the open questio=
ns to start from.</p>
<p><a class=3D"confluence-userlink user-mention current-user-mention" data-=
account-id=3D"712020:c9d98ec9-c34d-4652-978c-957d632b2a23" href=3D"https://=
